<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_ui_action` row that
    declares the `Resume` form button on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    The concrete scope identifier `x_casemgmt` is used consistently throughout
    this repository per ../docs/state-machine.md: "ServiceNow Update Set imports
    use a standard XML parser, so the scope id must be concrete in every record
    before the Update Set is exported." All sibling XML records in this Update
    Set use `x_casemgmt` byte-for-byte; this UI Action follows the same
    convention. The AAP Section 0.7.2 placeholder `x_[scope]_` is a TEMPLATE
    that resolves to `x_casemgmt_` at materialization time.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, row 4):
        From          To             Required condition / behavior
        Pending       In Progress    None; clears pending_reason
                                     (no blocking error condition - n/a)

    This UI Action is the user-facing ENTRY POINT for the Pending -> In Progress
    transition. It surfaces a "Resume" button on the case form whenever the case
    is currently in `Pending` status AND the current user is authorized
    (case_manager OR assigned case_agent). Clicking the button transitions the
    case back to In Progress and clears the pending_reason field. There is no
    user prompt - the transition is unconditional once the visibility gate is
    satisfied (per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 4: "None; clears pending_reason").

    SERVER-SIDE-ONLY PATTERN (contrast with sibling case_set_pending.xml):

        Unlike the Set Pending UI Action which uses a hybrid client+server
        pattern (it must collect the `pending_reason` value via prompt() on
        the client before submitting), this Resume UI Action runs ENTIRELY
        on the server. There is no input to collect - the transition has no
        required parameters. The single click invokes the server script
        directly via the platform's standard form-button verb pipeline,
        with no <onclick> JavaScript and no client-side function definition.

        Phase 1 - User clicks the "Resume" button.
        Phase 2 - The platform evaluates the visibility <condition> on the
                  server when the form was rendered; the button is shown
                  only if the condition was true.
        Phase 3 - The platform invokes the form-submit verb derived from
                  this UI Action's sys_name (`sysverb_x_casemgmt_case_resume`).
        Phase 4 - The platform binds `current` (the case GlideRecord),
                  `gs` (GlideSystem), `action` (UI Action helper), and
                  evaluates the <script> body in a server sandbox.
        Phase 5 - The script performs three layers of defense-in-depth
                  validation (role, status, assignment) before executing
                  the transition.
        Phase 6 - The script sets current.status = 'In Progress', explicitly
                  clears current.pending_reason = '', and calls
                  current.update() ONCE to persist both changes in a single
                  database transaction.
        Phase 7 - The script calls action.setRedirectURL(current) to refresh
                  the form so the operator sees the updated status and the
                  cleared pending_reason field.

        The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
        before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
          - x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml (skipped because previous
            status was Pending, not Closed)
          - x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml (skipped because
            current status is In Progress, not Draft)
          - x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml (re-validates
            assigned_agent membership; passes if the form state is consistent)
          - x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml (the COMPANION
            BR that ALSO clears pending_reason on this exact transition;
            see DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH PENDING_REASON CLEAR section below)
          - x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml (skipped because current status
            is In Progress, not Closed)

        The two Flow Designer flows (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        complaint_state_machine.xml) also fire on this update via their
        OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, but for the
        Pending -> In Progress edge the flow logic is a no-op (no required
        condition per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 4).

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.2.1):

        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
        line 79-114 - the central ArkCase case state-machine service. Its
        `changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState, ipAddress)` method:

            1) Loads the CaseFile by ID (line 85)
            2) Returns early if status unchanged (lines 88-91) - mirrored
               here by the defense-in-depth check `current.status != 'Pending'`
               (we do NOT redundantly re-check whether the new state equals
               the old state, because the visibility <condition> already
               gates the button on `current.status == 'Pending'`, and our
               only target newState is 'In Progress' so by definition
               we are changing state)
            3) Sets the new status (line 95: retval.setStatus(newState)) -
               mirrored here by `current.status = 'In Progress'`
            4) For "CLOSED" status, sets close timestamp (lines 97-100) -
               irrelevant for this UI Action which targets In Progress
            5) Saves the entity (line 102: getDao().save(retval)) -
               mirrored here by `current.update()`
            6) Raises an event for downstream listeners (line 106) -
               INTENTIONALLY OMITTED per the email-disabled constraint
               (AAP Section 0.7.2). ArkCase's raiseEvent() call would have
               triggered downstream notification listeners; the ServiceNow
               POC has no equivalent gs.eventQueue() call because email is
               disabled on the PDI and no other in-scope listeners need
               the event.

        That single method covered EVERY transition by string-matching the
        `newState` parameter. The ServiceNow target instead splits per-
        transition logic across:
          - This UI Action (Pending -> In Progress, the resume edge)
          - Sibling case_set_pending.xml (In Progress -> Pending, the pause edge)
          - The clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml business rule (the
            housekeeping companion that ALSO clears pending_reason on this
            same transition, providing belt-and-suspenders protection)
          - The two parent state-machine flows (which trigger on every
            status change but are no-ops for this transition)

    BUTTON VISIBILITY CONDITION (the <condition> field):

        The button is shown when ALL of the following are true:
          1) current.status == 'Pending'   (the source state of the
             Pending -> In Progress transition)
          2) The current user holds at least one of:
             - x_casemgmt_case_manager   (always permitted)
             - x_casemgmt_case_agent AND (current.assigned_agent ==
                gs.getUserID() OR current user is a member of
                current.assigned_group)
             (per AAP Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" rule for case_agent)

        The visibility check runs server-side (the <condition> field is
        evaluated by the platform when rendering the form). The
        defense-in-depth check inside the <script> body re-validates the
        same conditions on the server when the button is clicked, providing
        two layers of validation that protect against:
          - Form-tampering attacks where the user edits hidden form fields
            to attempt the transition from a non-Pending state
          - Race conditions where the user opens the form, the case
            transitions out of Pending in another browser tab, then the
            user clicks Resume in the original tab
          - Role escalation attempts where a viewer somehow gains access
            to the form

    DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH PENDING_REASON CLEAR (CRITICAL DESIGN DECISION):

        BOTH this UI Action AND ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_
        reason_on_inprogress.xml clear `pending_reason` on the Pending ->
        In Progress transition. This is INTENTIONAL belt-and-suspenders
        defense in depth, NOT a bug or redundancy:

          * This UI Action's explicit clear (`current.pending_reason = ''`)
            ensures the field is cleared even if the companion BR is later
            disabled, reordered to a position where it cannot fire, or
            removed entirely.

          * The companion BR's clear ensures the field is cleared even if
            this transition is performed via:
              - The Table API (e.g., REST integration patching status)
              - A scripted REST endpoint that bypasses this UI Action
              - The Update Set seed data import path
              - A scheduled job invoking GlideRecord.update()
              - Any other path that does not click the Resume button

          * The two clears happen in the SAME database transaction (this
            UI Action sets both fields BEFORE calling current.update();
            the BR fires DURING that single update via the before-update
            pipeline). There is no double-write or race condition.

          * Per AAP Section 0.7.2 "no out-of-scope workarounds when capability
            gaps are discovered": both layers are explicitly in scope as
            companion artifacts, not workarounds.

        The empty-string assignment `current.pending_reason = ''` is the
        canonical ServiceNow pattern for clearing a Choice field's value.
        Equivalent alternatives include `current.pending_reason.setNil()`
        and `current.setValue('pending_reason', null)`, but the empty
        string is the most universally recognized and works identically
        for non-mandatory Choice fields. Per ../dictionary/
        x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml the field is non-mandatory
        (mandatory=false), so clearing it is a legitimate end-state -
        the row remains valid with an empty pending_reason for any
        non-Pending status.

    CHOICE-VALUE BYTE-FOR-BYTE REQUIREMENTS (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim):

        The two case-status labels referenced in this UI Action are:

            'Pending'      (7 chars, single word, Title Case)
            'In Progress'  (11 chars, two words, literal SPACE)

        These MUST match the labels in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
        byte-for-byte. ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string
        by default (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the
        label text. Misspellings such as 'In_Progress' (underscore),
        'InProgress' (no space), 'in progress' (lowercase), or
        'IN PROGRESS' (uppercase) would silently never match and the
        UI Action would never fire.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table>x_casemgmt_case</table>             scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>          scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>      scoped application
        - <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
                                                     scoped roles
        - script body references current.status, current.pending_reason,
          current.assigned_agent, current.assigned_group, all on the
          scoped table x_casemgmt_case

        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.
        Zero global ACL or role mutations.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <roles> resolves the two roles BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case_manager,
          x_casemgmt_case_agent)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          GlideRecord and `gs.getUser()`, `gs.getUserID()` calls.
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_resume"), which is
          permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies
          to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to a
          record's own primary key.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This UI
        Action contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls,
        and zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the status
        update, the pending_reason clear, and an action.setRedirectURL
        refresh.

    NO PII CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body, code comments, description text, hint text, and
        all error messages contain zero real names, real email addresses,
        real phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other
        personally identifiable information. The UI Action operates
        exclusively on synthetic case-status enumerations (Pending,
        In Progress) and synthetic Choice-field clears.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_ui_action record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (the table this UI Action is bound to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads and the script writes)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml
              (the field the script writes/clears)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads for the
               "Assigned only" check)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads for the
               "Assigned only" check)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
              (the Pending and In Progress Choice values)
            - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
              (the COMPANION before-update BR that ALSO clears
               pending_reason on this transition; defense in depth)
            - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml
              (the manager role referenced by <roles> and condition)
            - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml
              (the agent role referenced by <roles> and condition)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (the scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (the scope record)

        And BEFORE:
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_04.xml
              (the Pending-status demo case that exercises this UI Action;
               loading the demo case before this UI Action would still
               work since UI Actions are not invoked at load time, but
               the AAP-mandated load order keeps user-facing behavior
               artifacts ahead of demo data)
            - ../update-set/x_casemgmt_case_management_update_set.xml
              (the final aggregated Update Set that includes this record)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:

        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_case_resume")
               = d48fd05fbca31c2194cac4b8645a2dbc
        32-character lowercase hex. Recomputable via:
            printf '%s' 'x_casemgmt_case_resume' | md5sum | cut -c1-32

        Deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent re-import on a
        fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set produces the same
        sys_id, which collides on the existing record and updates it in
        place rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same convention
        used by the sibling Business Rules in
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_*.xml and the sibling UI Action
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_set_pending.xml.

    ORDER WITHIN UI ACTION SEQUENCE:

        order=400 places Resume in the workflow sequence between
        Set Pending (300) and Resolve (500):
            1) Open               (order=100, FIRST  - Draft -> Open)
            2) Start Progress     (order=200       - Open -> In Progress)
            3) Set Pending        (order=300       - In Progress -> Pending)
            4) Resume             (order=400, THIS  - Pending -> In Progress)
            5) Resolve            (order=500       - In Progress -> Resolved)
            6) Close              (order=600, LAST  - Resolved -> Closed)

        The ordering is for UI display only - the platform renders form
        buttons in ascending order. Only one button is visible at a time
        (each visibility <condition> matches a different status), so the
        ordering does not affect runtime correctness.

    FORM_STYLE = primary:

        Resume is the AFFIRMATIVE FORWARD action when the case is in
        Pending status. The user wants to resume work on the case, so
        the button is rendered with the platform's primary visual style
        (typically a filled-color button) to draw attention. This contrasts
        with Set Pending, which uses form_style=secondary because pausing
        a case is a less common, less attention-grabbing action.

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error". This
          UI Action implements the Pending -> In Progress transition (per
          AAP Section 0.5.5 row 4). Although the AAP marks this transition
          as having "no required condition" (n/a in the blocking-error
          column), the implementation still enforces:
            - The user must hold case_manager OR case_agent role
            - For case_agents, the "Assigned only" rule applies
            - The case must be in Pending status (not In Progress, not
              already In Progress, not Closed, etc.)
          Each guard surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage if violated.
          The defense-in-depth status re-check prevents stale-form
          submissions from corrupting the state machine.

        - Gate 3 (ACLs): "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot
          write; case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager
          has full access". This UI Action's visibility <condition> and
          server-side defense-in-depth check both encode the role rules
          from AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim. case_viewer is excluded by the
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
          field. case_agent on an unassigned case is excluded by the
          "Assigned only" sub-condition.

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and absence of any external
          lookups guarantee this UI Action re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors.

    COMPANION ARTIFACTS:

        This UI Action handles the Pending -> In Progress transition at
        the FORM-LEVEL (button click). Companion artifacts:

          - ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_set_pending.xml
            (the mirror UI Action that handles the reverse In Progress ->
             Pending transition)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
            (the housekeeping BR that ALSO clears pending_reason on this
             same transition; together with this UI Action they form a
             defense-in-depth pair that guarantees pending_reason is
             always cleared on Pending -> In Progress regardless of which
             interface initiates the transition)
          - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=General Inquiry; fires
             on this transition but is a no-op because Pending -> In
             Progress has no required condition)
          - ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=Complaint; fires on
             this transition but is a no-op because Pending -> In Progress
             has no required condition)

        The UI Action provides the FORM-LEVEL entry point (button). The
        BR provides the FIELD-LEVEL housekeeping (clear pending_reason).
        The flows provide the WORKFLOW-LEVEL hook (no-op here). They are
        complementary, not redundant.

    REGENERATION NOTE:

        This XML file is generated as part of the Update Set authoring
        process. To regenerate:
          1. Re-run the source-of-truth template fill from the AAP.
          2. Recompute the deterministic sys_id from MD5(sys_name).
          3. Re-export the Update Set XML from the PDI.

        Manual edits to this file are valid but should be reflected in
        ../docs/state-machine.md if they alter the transition matrix or
        error message text.
-->
<record_update table="sys_ui_action">
    <sys_ui_action action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <action_name>x_casemgmt_case_resume</action_name>
        <active>true</active>
        <client>false</client>
        <comments>UI Action that resumes a Pending case back to In Progress status, clearing pending_reason. Visible to x_casemgmt_case_manager (always) and x_casemgmt_case_agent (only when assigned to the case via assigned_agent or member of assigned_group, per AAP Section 0.5.6 Assigned-only rule). Server-side-only (no client prompt) - the transition has no required parameters per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 4 verbatim: "Pending -&gt; In Progress: None; clears pending_reason". Performs the transition on the server with defense-in-depth re-validation of role, status, and assignment. Explicitly clears pending_reason in addition to the companion business rule ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml (order=400) which also clears it during the same database update transaction; together they form a belt-and-suspenders defense-in-depth pair. Contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls per the email-disabled constraint, zero hardcoded sys_id literals, and zero PII.</comments>
        <condition><![CDATA[current.status == 'Pending' && (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager') || (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent') && (current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() || (current.assigned_group && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())))))]]></condition>
        <form_action>true</form_action>
        <form_button>true</form_button>
        <form_button_v2>false</form_button_v2>
        <form_context_menu>false</form_context_menu>
        <form_link>false</form_link>
        <form_menu_button_v2>false</form_menu_button_v2>
        <form_style>primary</form_style>
        <format_for_configurable_workspace>false</format_for_configurable_workspace>
        <hint>Resume work on this case (clears pending_reason).</hint>
        <isolate_script>true</isolate_script>
        <list_action>false</list_action>
        <list_banner_button>false</list_banner_button>
        <list_button>false</list_button>
        <list_choice>false</list_choice>
        <list_context_menu>false</list_context_menu>
        <list_link>false</list_link>
        <list_save_with_form_button>false</list_save_with_form_button>
        <messages/>
        <name>Resume</name>
        <onclick/>
        <order>400</order>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 4 (Pending -> In Progress):
    //   "None; clears pending_reason"
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.1: blocking errors must appear on the form.
    //
    // This is the SERVER-side click handler for the Resume form button. It
    // runs in the server sandbox (no window, has current GlideRecord, has
    // gs and action) and is responsible for:
    //   1) Defense-in-depth role re-check (case_manager OR case_agent).
    //   2) Defense-in-depth status re-check (must be 'Pending').
    //   3) Defense-in-depth "Assigned only" re-check for case_agents.
    //   4) Status persistence (current.status = 'In Progress'; current.update()).
    //   5) Explicit pending_reason clear (current.pending_reason = '')
    //      as defense-in-depth alongside the companion business rule
    //      ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
    //      (order=400) which ALSO clears pending_reason on this same
    //      transition during the same database update transaction.
    //   6) Form refresh (action.setRedirectURL(current)).
    //
    // Each of the three guards above maps to a row in the AAP Section
    // 0.5.6 ACL matrix or the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition map:
    //   - Guard 1: Role check enforces "Only role X can perform action Y".
    //   - Guard 2: Status check enforces "Only Pending -> In Progress".
    //   - Guard 3: Assigned only check enforces case_agent's assigned-only
    //     write privilege (case_manager bypasses this guard).
    //
    // All three guards must pass before current.update() is called.
    // Any guard failure surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage and
    // returns without persisting.

    // Guard 1: Role check. The user must hold case_manager OR case_agent.
    // (case_viewer is excluded by the <roles> field already, but the
    // server-side re-check protects against the rare case where a user
    // lost the role between form load and form submit.)
    if (!gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager') && !gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent')) {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers and assigned case agents can resume cases.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 2: Status check. The case must currently be Pending.
    // Re-checking on the server protects against a stale-form attack
    // where the user opens the form when status is Pending, the case
    // transitions in another tab, then the user submits from the
    // original tab. The check uses string comparison against the
    // verbatim Title Case 'Pending' label per AAP Section 0.5.7.
    if (current.status != 'Pending') {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only Pending cases can be resumed.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 3: Assigned only check for case_agents. case_managers
    // bypass this guard (they can resume any case). For case_agents,
    // the case must be assigned to them directly OR they must be a
    // member of the assigned_group, per AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim:
    // "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
    // assigned_group contains current user".
    //
    // The .toString() coercion on assigned_group resolves the GlideElement
    // reference to its sys_id string, which is what gs.getUser().isMemberOf()
    // expects. Without the coercion, the GlideElement-vs-string comparison
    // can behave inconsistently across releases.
    if (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent') && !gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')) {
        var groupIdResume = current.assigned_group ? current.assigned_group.toString() : '';
        var isAssigned = (current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()) ||
                         (groupIdResume && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupIdResume));
        if (!isAssigned) {
            gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers and assigned case agents can resume cases.');
            action.setRedirectURL(current);
            return;
        }
    }

    // All three guards passed. Perform the Pending -> In Progress
    // transition. The status assignment uses the verbatim Title Case
    // 'In Progress' label (note the literal SPACE between 'In' and
    // 'Progress') per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the sibling choice file
    // ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml.
    //
    // Both field changes (status and pending_reason) happen in a single
    // current.update() call. The before-update business rules
    // (block_terminal_closed, block_draft_backtransition,
    // validate_assigned_agent_membership, clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress)
    // all run BEFORE this single update writes to the database.
    //
    // Explicitly clearing pending_reason here is INTENTIONAL defense in
    // depth alongside the companion BR clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
    // (order=400) which ALSO clears it. The two clears happen in the
    // SAME database transaction (this UI Action sets the field BEFORE
    // calling current.update(); the BR fires DURING that single update
    // via the before-update pipeline). There is no double-write or race
    // condition. Together they ensure pending_reason is always cleared
    // on Pending -> In Progress regardless of which interface initiates
    // the transition (form button, Table API, scripted REST, scheduled
